Note: ============================================================================
Note: HIR->Ruby Backend - Complete Ruby code generation from HIR
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Part of the Translation translation system
Note: Generates idiomatic Ruby code from High-level Intermediate Representation.
Note: Consumes exactly the node shapes the ruby_to_hir frontend emits, recovering
Note: Ruby-only operators and constructs from the "ruby_*" metadata tags so the
Note: source -> HIR -> source round-trip preserves Ruby semantics.
Note: ============================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_nodes.runa" as HIR
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as ListCore
Import "compiler/internal/string_utils.runa" as StringUtils

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Code Generation Context
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Threads the HIR-to-Ruby generation pipeline so emission helpers manage nested
indentation and accumulate errors without positional parameters. hir_module is
the dispatcher's root HIR node; indent_level is bumped by indent/dedent and
rendered as indent_level copies of indent_string. errors collects messages;
had_error short-circuits downstream emission once a generation error occurs.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Idiomatic value-of-type struct: construction allocates the heap home directly
and the binding is the struct pointer. Helpers re-bind the pointer with a typed
Let; field mutations write in place so no read/write round-trips are needed.
@End Implementation
Type called "RubyCodeGenContext":
    hir_module as Integer          Note: HIR module being generated from
    indent_level as Integer        Note: Current indentation level
    indent_string as String        Note: Indentation string (2 spaces, Ruby idiom)
    errors as Integer              Note: List of generation errors
    had_error as Integer           Note: Boolean: 1 if error occurred
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Context Creation and Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The dispatcher hands us only the HIR module pointer. Indent level starts at 0
with a 2-space step matching idiomatic Ruby. The errors list is eagerly created
so downstream code never has to null-check before appending.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_codegen_context" takes hir_module as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ctx be a value of type RubyCodeGenContext with
        hir_module as hir_module,
        indent_level as 0,
        indent_string as "  ",
        errors as proc list_create from ListCore,
        had_error as 0

    Return ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
Recording errors appends the message to the errors list and flips the had_error
sentinel; downstream emit helpers short-circuit on had_error to avoid producing
syntactically corrupted Ruby after a generation failure.
@End Reasoning
Process called "codegen_error" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, message as String:
    Let ctx as RubyCodeGenContext be ctx_ptr
    proc list_append from ListCore with ctx.errors, message
    Set ctx.had_error to 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Indentation Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Indentation is a struct field, not a global, because nested generator
invocations recursively enter scopes (method-in-class, block-in-call). Mutating
through the typed binding keeps the increment visible to sibling helpers.
@End Reasoning
Process called "indent" takes ctx_ptr as Integer:
    Let ctx as RubyCodeGenContext be ctx_ptr
    Set ctx.indent_level to ctx.indent_level plus 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Floor-clamps at zero rather than allowing negative levels, which would corrupt
get_indent's repetition loop. A buggy generator emitting a stray dedent must
still produce parseable Ruby, hence the defensive guard.
@End Reasoning
Process called "dedent" takes ctx_ptr as Integer:
    Let ctx as RubyCodeGenContext be ctx_ptr
    If ctx.indent_level is greater than 0:
        Set ctx.indent_level to ctx.indent_level minus 1
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
We materialize the indent string per call rather than caching it because
indent_level changes constantly during nested emission; a cache would have to be
invalidated on every indent/dedent.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_indent" takes ctx_ptr as Integer returns String:
    Let ctx as RubyCodeGenContext be ctx_ptr
    Let indent be ""

    Let count be 0
    While count is less than ctx.indent_level:
        Set indent to proc string_concat from StringUtils with indent, ctx.indent_string
        Set count to count plus 1
    End While

    Return indent
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Metadata Helpers
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A frequent backend idiom is "is this metadata flag set to the truthy string".
Centralising the null-safe string-equality test against the HIR metadata read
keeps the call sites terse and avoids repeating the 0-handle guard that
string_equals already performs but which we want to read as a single predicate.
@End Reasoning
Process called "meta_is" takes node as Integer, key as String, expected as String returns Integer:
    Let value be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with node, key
    Return proc string_equals from StringCore with value, expected
End Process

@Reasoning:
Several constructs are marked present by a "true"-valued metadata flag. This
predicate returns 1 when the named flag equals "true" so callers read as a
boolean test without spelling out the comparison each time.
@End Reasoning
Process called "meta_flag" takes node as Integer, key as String returns Integer:
    Return proc meta_is with node, key, "true"
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: String Escaping
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Order matters: backslashes must be doubled BEFORE any other escape inserts new
backslashes. Then double-quotes, newlines and tabs are escaped. This covers the
characters that would terminate a Ruby double-quoted literal or break its
single-line invariant. Built char-by-char to avoid arena-requiring replace.
@End Reasoning
@Security_Scope:
This is the primary sanitization barrier between untrusted source content and
generated Ruby. Any new escape sequence must be added here before this generator
can be considered safe for adversarial input.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "escape_ruby_string" takes str as Integer returns String:
    Let result be ""
    Let len be proc string_length from StringCore with str
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than len:
        Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with str, i

        If ch is equal to 92:
            Note: backslash
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\\"
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\\"
        Otherwise:
            If ch is equal to 34:
                Note: double quote
                Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\\"
                Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\""
            Otherwise:
                If ch is equal to 10:
                    Note: newline
                    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\\"
                    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "n"
                Otherwise:
                    If ch is equal to 9:
                        Note: tab
                        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\\"
                        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "t"
                    Otherwise:
                        Let single be proc char_to_string from StringCore with ch
                        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, single
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Expression Generation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Central dispatch from HIR node kind to a specialised expression generator. Order
of checks tracks frequency (literals and identifiers first) so common cases
short-circuit early. Unknown node kinds record a codegen error and return empty
string so the caller still produces syntactically valid Ruby.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_expression" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, expr_node as Integer returns String:
    Let node_type be proc hir_node_type from HIR with expr_node

    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_INT_LITERAL:
        Return proc generate_int_literal with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If
    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_FLOAT_LITERAL:
        Return proc generate_float_literal with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If
    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_STRING_LITERAL:
        Return proc generate_string_literal with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If
    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_BOOL_LITERAL:
        Let bval be proc hir_get_bool_literal_value from HIR with expr_node
        If bval is equal to 1:
            Return "true"
        End If
        Return "false"
    End If
    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_NULL_LITERAL:
        Return "nil"
    End If
    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_IDENTIFIER:
        Return proc generate_identifier with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If
    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_BINARY_EXPR:
        Return proc generate_binary_expression with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If
    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_UNARY_EXPR:
        Return proc generate_unary_expression with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If
    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_TERNARY_EXPR:
        Return proc generate_ternary_expression with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If
    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_CALL_EXPR:
        Return proc generate_call_expression with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If
    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_INDEX_EXPR:
        Return proc generate_index_expression with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If
    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_MEMBER_EXPR:
        Return proc generate_member_expression with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If
    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_ASSIGN_EXPR:
        Return proc generate_assign_expression with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If
    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_LAMBDA:
        Return proc generate_lambda_expression with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If
    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_LIST_LITERAL:
        Return proc generate_list_literal with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If
    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_MAP_LITERAL:
        Return proc generate_map_literal with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If

    proc codegen_error with ctx_ptr, "Unknown Ruby expression type"
    Return ""
End Process

@Reasoning:
Integer literals re-emit the original Ruby lexeme when the frontend preserved it
in "ruby_int_lexeme" (so hex/underscore forms survive), falling back to the
decimal string of the stored native integer when no lexeme is present.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_int_literal" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let lexeme be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with node, "ruby_int_lexeme"
    If lexeme is not equal to 0:
        Return lexeme
    End If
    Let ival be proc hir_get_int_literal_value from HIR with node
    Return proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with ival
End Process

@Reasoning:
Float literals re-emit the original lexeme from "ruby_float_lexeme" when present
so the exact textual form (trailing zeros, exponents) round-trips; otherwise the
stored native float is formatted with six fractional digits.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_float_literal" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let lexeme be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with node, "ruby_float_lexeme"
    If lexeme is not equal to 0:
        Return lexeme
    End If
    Let fval be proc hir_get_float_literal_value from HIR with node
    Return proc float_to_string from StringUtils with fval, 6, 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
String-carrier literals re-emit one of several Ruby forms based on the frontend
tag: a symbol prints ":name", a regexp prints its preserved lexeme verbatim, an
interpolated string prints its preserved lexeme verbatim (the #{} segments are
inside), and a plain string is double-quoted with escaping. The original lexeme
metadata is consulted first so the exact source spelling round-trips.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_string_literal" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    If proc meta_flag with node, "ruby_symbol" is equal to 1:
        Let sym_name be proc hir_get_string_literal_value from HIR with node
        Return proc string_concat from StringUtils with ":", sym_name
    End If

    If proc meta_flag with node, "ruby_regexp" is equal to 1:
        Return proc hir_get_string_literal_value from HIR with node
    End If

    If proc meta_flag with node, "ruby_interp" is equal to 1:
        Let interp_lexeme be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with node, "ruby_string_lexeme"
        If interp_lexeme is not equal to 0:
            Return interp_lexeme
        End If
    End If

    Let sval be proc hir_get_string_literal_value from HIR with node
    Let escaped be proc escape_ruby_string with sval
    Let quoted be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "\"", escaped
    Set quoted to proc string_concat from StringUtils with quoted, "\""
    Return quoted
End Process

@Reasoning:
HIR identifiers re-emit their stored name verbatim, which already carries Ruby
sigils (@x, @@x, $x) and the "self" keyword unchanged. The frontend kept the full
source token in the name, so no reconstruction from "ruby_var_kind"/"ruby_self"
metadata is required - those tags exist for analysis, not re-spelling.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_identifier" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let name be proc hir_get_identifier_name from HIR with node
    If name is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If
    Return name
End Process

@Reasoning:
Binary expressions emit "left OP right" with single-space padding. The exact Ruby
operator spelling is recovered from "ruby_operator" metadata (so **, <=>, ===, =~,
!~ that share an HIR opcode round-trip), falling back to the HIR-opcode mapping
when no metadata is present. The HIR tree already encodes Ruby precedence, so no
parentheses are inserted.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_binary_expression" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let operator be proc hir_get_binary_op from HIR with node
    Let left_node be proc hir_get_binary_left from HIR with node
    Let right_node be proc hir_get_binary_right from HIR with node

    Let left_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, left_node
    Let right_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, right_node

    Let op_str be proc map_hir_operator_to_ruby with operator
    Let ruby_op be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with node, "ruby_operator"
    If ruby_op is not equal to 0:
        Set op_str to ruby_op
    End If

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with left_code, " "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, op_str
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, right_code
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
A linear cascade rather than a dictionary lookup because HIR operator codes are
dense. Ruby spellings match HIR for arithmetic/comparison; logical and/or use the
"&&"/"||" symbolic forms (the "ruby_operator" metadata overrides to the keyword
"and"/"or" when the source used them). Fallback "+" keeps a missing mapping
syntactically valid.
@End Reasoning
Process called "map_hir_operator_to_ruby" takes operator as Integer returns String:
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_ADD:
        Return "+"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_SUBTRACT:
        Return "-"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_MULTIPLY:
        Return "*"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_DIVIDE:
        Return "/"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_MODULO:
        Return "%"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_INT_DIVIDE:
        Return "/"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_EQUAL:
        Return "=="
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_NOT_EQUAL:
        Return "!="
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_LESS_THAN:
        Return "<"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_GREATER_THAN:
        Return ">"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_LESS_EQUAL:
        Return "<="
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_GREATER_EQUAL:
        Return ">="
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_LOGICAL_AND:
        Return "&&"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_LOGICAL_OR:
        Return "||"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_BITWISE_AND:
        Return "&"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_BITWISE_OR:
        Return "|"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_BITWISE_XOR:
        Return "^"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_SHIFT_LEFT:
        Return "<<"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_SHIFT_RIGHT:
        Return ">>"
    End If
    Return "+"  Note: Default fallback
End Process

@Reasoning:
Unary emission re-prefixes the HIR opcode's Ruby spelling: "-" for negate, "~" for
bitwise not, and the "not" keyword vs "!" symbol for logical not (chosen by the
"ruby_not_keyword" tag). A frontend-tagged identity "+" ("ruby_unary"="plus")
re-prefixes "+". The "not " keyword form requires a trailing space.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_unary_expression" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let operator be proc hir_get_unary_op from HIR with node
    Let operand_node be proc hir_get_unary_operand from HIR with node
    Let operand_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, operand_node

    If proc meta_is with node, "ruby_unary", "plus" is equal to 1:
        Return proc string_concat from StringUtils with "+", operand_code
    End If

    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_NEGATE:
        Return proc string_concat from StringUtils with "-", operand_code
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_BITWISE_NOT:
        Return proc string_concat from StringUtils with "~", operand_code
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_LOGICAL_NOT:
        If proc meta_flag with node, "ruby_not_keyword" is equal to 1:
            Return proc string_concat from StringUtils with "not ", operand_code
        End If
        Return proc string_concat from StringUtils with "!", operand_code
    End If

    Return operand_code
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ternary emission produces "cond ? then : else" with the canonical Ruby spacing.
The HIR tree already reflects precedence so no parentheses are added.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_ternary_expression" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let cond_node be proc hir_get_ternary_condition from HIR with node
    Let then_node be proc hir_get_ternary_then from HIR with node
    Let else_node be proc hir_get_ternary_else from HIR with node

    Let cond_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, cond_node
    Let then_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, then_node
    Let else_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, else_node

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with cond_code, " ? "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, then_code
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " : "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, else_code
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Call emission has several Ruby-specific shapes recovered from metadata: a range
call re-emits "low..high"/"low...high"; a "defined?" call re-emits the keyword
form; a "super" call re-emits bare or parenthesised super; an "alias_method"/
"undef_method" synthetic call re-emits the keyword statement. Otherwise it is an
ordinary "callee(args)" with a trailing "do |params| ... end" block when the call
carried one.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_call_expression" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    If proc meta_flag with node, "ruby_range" is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_range_call with ctx_ptr, node
    End If
    If proc meta_flag with node, "ruby_defined" is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_defined_call with ctx_ptr, node
    End If
    If proc meta_flag with node, "ruby_super" is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_super_call with ctx_ptr, node
    End If
    If proc meta_flag with node, "ruby_alias" is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_keyword_pair_call with ctx_ptr, node, "alias"
    End If
    If proc meta_flag with node, "ruby_undef" is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_undef_call with ctx_ptr, node
    End If

    Let callee_node be proc hir_get_call_callee from HIR with node
    Let callee_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, callee_node

    Note: Split arguments into ordinary args and the trailing call-block, if any.
    Let args_list be proc hir_get_positional_args from HIR with node
    Let arg_count be 0
    If args_list is not equal to 0:
        Set arg_count to proc list_length from ListCore with args_list
    End If

    Let block_node be 0
    Let args_code be ""
    Let emitted be 0

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than arg_count:
        Let arg_node be proc list_get from ListCore with args_list, i

        If proc meta_flag with arg_node, "ruby_call_block" is equal to 1:
            Set block_node to arg_node
        Otherwise:
            Let arg_code be proc generate_argument with ctx_ptr, arg_node
            If emitted is greater than 0:
                Set args_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with args_code, ", "
            End If
            Set args_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with args_code, arg_code
            Set emitted to emitted plus 1
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Let result be callee_code
    If emitted is greater than 0:
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "("
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, args_code
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ")"
    End If

    If block_node is not equal to 0:
        Let block_code be proc generate_call_block with ctx_ptr, block_node
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, block_code
    End If

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Each call argument re-prefixes its Ruby form from metadata: a splat arg gets "*",
a double-splat gets "**", a keyword arg gets "name: ", a block-pass arg gets "&".
Plain arguments emit their expression directly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_argument" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, arg_node as Integer returns String:
    Let kwarg be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with arg_node, "ruby_kwarg"
    If kwarg is not equal to 0:
        Let kw_value be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, arg_node
        Let kw_result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with kwarg, ": "
        Set kw_result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with kw_result, kw_value
        Return kw_result
    End If

    If proc meta_flag with arg_node, "ruby_doublesplat" is equal to 1:
        Let ds_value be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, arg_node
        Return proc string_concat from StringUtils with "**", ds_value
    End If
    If proc meta_flag with arg_node, "ruby_splat" is equal to 1:
        Let sp_value be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, arg_node
        Return proc string_concat from StringUtils with "*", sp_value
    End If
    If proc meta_flag with arg_node, "ruby_blockpass" is equal to 1:
        Let bp_value be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, arg_node
        Return proc string_concat from StringUtils with "&", bp_value
    End If

    Return proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, arg_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
A range call re-emits "low..high" (or "low...high" when the exclusive tag is set)
from its two arguments, reproducing Ruby's range literal that the frontend lowered
to a synthetic Range call.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_range_call" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let args_list be proc hir_get_positional_args from HIR with node
    Let low be proc list_get from ListCore with args_list, 0
    Let high be proc list_get from ListCore with args_list, 1

    Let low_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, low
    Let high_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, high

    Let sep be ".."
    If proc meta_flag with node, "ruby_range_exclusive" is equal to 1:
        Set sep to "..."
    End If

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with low_code, sep
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, high_code
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
A defined? call re-emits "defined?(operand)" from its single argument, restoring
the keyword-with-parens form the frontend preserved via the "ruby_defined" tag.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_defined_call" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let args_list be proc hir_get_positional_args from HIR with node
    Let operand be proc list_get from ListCore with args_list, 0
    Let operand_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, operand

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "defined?(", operand_code
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ")"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
A super call re-emits bare "super" when the "ruby_super_bare" tag is set, else
"super(args)" from the call's arguments, reproducing Ruby's two super forms which
differ in argument-forwarding semantics.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_super_call" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    If proc meta_flag with node, "ruby_super_bare" is equal to 1:
        Return "super"
    End If

    Let args_list be proc hir_get_positional_args from HIR with node
    Let arg_count be 0
    If args_list is not equal to 0:
        Set arg_count to proc list_length from ListCore with args_list
    End If

    Let args_code be ""
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than arg_count:
        Let arg_node be proc list_get from ListCore with args_list, i
        Let arg_code be proc generate_argument with ctx_ptr, arg_node
        If i is greater than 0:
            Set args_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with args_code, ", "
        End If
        Set args_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with args_code, arg_code
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "super(", args_code
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ")"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
"alias new old" re-emits the keyword followed by the two name arguments separated
by a space (Ruby's alias keyword takes bareword names without parentheses). The
keyword is supplied by the caller so the same shape could serve related forms.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_keyword_pair_call" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer, keyword as String returns String:
    Let args_list be proc hir_get_positional_args from HIR with node
    Let new_arg be proc list_get from ListCore with args_list, 0
    Let old_arg be proc list_get from ListCore with args_list, 1

    Let new_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, new_arg
    Let old_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, old_arg

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with keyword, " "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, new_code
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, old_code
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
"undef a, b, c" re-emits the keyword followed by the comma-separated name
arguments, restoring Ruby's undef statement from the synthetic undef_method call.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_undef_call" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let args_list be proc hir_get_positional_args from HIR with node
    Let arg_count be 0
    If args_list is not equal to 0:
        Set arg_count to proc list_length from ListCore with args_list
    End If

    Let names_code be ""
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than arg_count:
        Let arg_node be proc list_get from ListCore with args_list, i
        Let arg_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, arg_node
        If i is greater than 0:
            Set names_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with names_code, ", "
        End If
        Set names_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with names_code, arg_code
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return proc string_concat from StringUtils with "undef ", names_code
End Process

@Reasoning:
A trailing call block re-emits Ruby's "do |params| ... end" form. The block is a
HIR lambda whose parameters become the pipe-delimited block parameters and whose
body statements are emitted on their own indented lines, closing with "end". The
do..end form is always valid regardless of body length, so it is preferred over
the brace form for the multi-statement case.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_call_block" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let params_code be proc generate_block_params with ctx_ptr, node
    Let body_node be proc hir_get_lambda_block_body from HIR with node

    Let result be " do"
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with params_code, "" is equal to 0:
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " |"
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, params_code
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "|"
    End If
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\n"

    proc indent with ctx_ptr
    Let body_code be proc generate_statement with ctx_ptr, body_node
    proc dedent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, body_code

    Let end_indent be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, end_indent
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "end"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Index access re-emits "object[index]". A multi-index access (tagged
"ruby_multi_index") unpacks the list-literal index into comma-separated keys to
reproduce Ruby's obj[a, b] form; a single index emits the lone key.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_index_expression" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let object_node be proc hir_get_index_object from HIR with node
    Let index_node be proc hir_get_index_value from HIR with node
    Let object_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, object_node

    Let keys_code be ""
    If proc meta_flag with node, "ruby_multi_index" is equal to 1:
        Let elements be proc hir_get_list_elements from HIR with index_node
        Let elem_count be proc list_length from ListCore with elements
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than elem_count:
            Let elem be proc list_get from ListCore with elements, i
            Let elem_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, elem
            If i is greater than 0:
                Set keys_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with keys_code, ", "
            End If
            Set keys_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with keys_code, elem_code
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    Otherwise:
        Set keys_code to proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, index_node
    End If

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with object_code, "["
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, keys_code
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "]"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Member access re-emits "object.name", or "object&.name" for safe navigation, or
"scope::Name" for a constant scope reference (tagged "ruby_scope"="postfix"). The
member name is a String spliced directly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_member_expression" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let object_node be proc hir_get_member_object from HIR with node
    Let member_name be proc hir_get_member_name from HIR with node
    Let object_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, object_node

    Let sep be "."
    If proc meta_is with node, "ruby_scope", "postfix" is equal to 1:
        Set sep to "::"
    Otherwise If proc meta_flag with node, "ruby_safe_nav" is equal to 1:
        Set sep to "&."
    End If

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with object_code, sep
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, member_name
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Assignment-as-expression re-emits "lhs OP rhs". The compound operator is recovered
from "ruby_op_assign" metadata (so +=, ||=, **= round-trip), falling back to the
HIR assign-opcode mapping and finally "=" for the simple case.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_assign_expression" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let lhs_node be proc hir_get_assign_lhs from HIR with node
    Let rhs_node be proc hir_get_assign_rhs from HIR with node
    Let op_code be proc hir_get_assign_op from HIR with node

    Let lhs_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, lhs_node
    Let rhs_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, rhs_node

    Let op_str be proc map_hir_assign_to_ruby with op_code
    Let ruby_op be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with node, "ruby_op_assign"
    If ruby_op is not equal to 0:
        Set op_str to ruby_op
    End If

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with lhs_code, " "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, op_str
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, rhs_code
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Maps the HIR assign opcode to its Ruby compound-operator spelling for the cases
the frontend lowered without preserving a "ruby_op_assign" lexeme; the simple
assign and any unmapped opcode default to "=".
@End Reasoning
Process called "map_hir_assign_to_ruby" takes op_code as Integer returns String:
    If op_code is equal to HIR.HIR_ASSIGN_ADD:
        Return "+="
    End If
    If op_code is equal to HIR.HIR_ASSIGN_SUBTRACT:
        Return "-="
    End If
    If op_code is equal to HIR.HIR_ASSIGN_MULTIPLY:
        Return "*="
    End If
    If op_code is equal to HIR.HIR_ASSIGN_DIVIDE:
        Return "/="
    End If
    If op_code is equal to HIR.HIR_ASSIGN_MODULO:
        Return "%="
    End If
    If op_code is equal to HIR.HIR_ASSIGN_NULL_COALESCE:
        Return "||="
    End If
    Return "="
End Process

@Reasoning:
A lambda expression re-emits Ruby's stabby "-> (params) { body }" form by default,
or "lambda { |params| body }", "proc { |params| body }", or a do..end block based
on the "ruby_lambda_kind" tag. The body statements are emitted inline within an
always-valid multi-line braces/do delimiter.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_lambda_expression" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let kind be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with node, "ruby_lambda_kind"
    Let params_code be proc generate_block_params with ctx_ptr, node
    Let body_node be proc hir_get_lambda_block_body from HIR with node

    Let is_arrow be proc string_equals from StringCore with kind, "arrow"
    Let is_proc be proc string_equals from StringCore with kind, "proc"

    Let header be ""
    Let closer be "}"
    Let has_params be 0
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with params_code, "" is equal to 0:
        Set has_params to 1
    End If

    If is_arrow is equal to 1:
        Set header to "->"
        If has_params is equal to 1:
            Set header to proc string_concat from StringUtils with header, " ("
            Set header to proc string_concat from StringUtils with header, params_code
            Set header to proc string_concat from StringUtils with header, ")"
        End If
        Set header to proc string_concat from StringUtils with header, " {"
    Otherwise:
        If is_proc is equal to 1:
            Set header to "proc {"
        Otherwise:
            Set header to "lambda {"
        End If
        If has_params is equal to 1:
            Set header to proc string_concat from StringUtils with header, " |"
            Set header to proc string_concat from StringUtils with header, params_code
            Set header to proc string_concat from StringUtils with header, "|"
        End If
    End If

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with header, "\n"

    proc indent with ctx_ptr
    Let body_code be proc generate_statement with ctx_ptr, body_node
    proc dedent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, body_code

    Let end_indent be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, end_indent
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, closer
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Block/lambda parameters share the function-parameter machinery: we read the
callable's parameter list and join the names with ", ", re-prefixing splat/
doublesplat/block kinds from each parameter's "ruby_param_kind" tag so the block
header reproduces *args / **kwargs / &blk.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_block_params" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let params be proc hir_get_lambda_parameters from HIR with node
    Let param_list be proc hir_get_parameter_list from HIR with params
    Let param_count be 0
    If param_list is not equal to 0:
        Set param_count to proc list_length from ListCore with param_list
    End If

    Let result be ""
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than param_count:
        Let param_node be proc list_get from ListCore with param_list, i
        Let param_code be proc generate_parameter with ctx_ptr, param_node
        If i is greater than 0:
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ", "
        End If
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, param_code
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
A single parameter re-emits its Ruby spelling: the name re-prefixed with "*", "**"
or "&" per "ruby_param_kind", suffixed with ":" for a keyword parameter, and a
" = default" (or " default" for keyword) appended when the frontend stored a
default expression in metadata.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_parameter" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, param_node as Integer returns String:
    Let name be proc hir_get_parameter_name from HIR with param_node
    Let kind be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with param_node, "ruby_param_kind"

    Let result be name
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with kind, "splat" is equal to 1:
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with "*", name
    Otherwise If proc string_equals from StringCore with kind, "doublesplat" is equal to 1:
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with "**", name
    Otherwise If proc string_equals from StringCore with kind, "block" is equal to 1:
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with "&", name
    Otherwise If proc string_equals from StringCore with kind, "kwarg" is equal to 1:
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with name, ":"
    End If

    If proc meta_flag with param_node, "ruby_param_has_default" is equal to 1:
        Let default_hir be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with param_node, "ruby_param_default"
        If default_hir is not equal to 0:
            Let default_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, default_hir
            If proc string_equals from StringCore with kind, "kwarg" is equal to 1:
                Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " "
                Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, default_code
            Otherwise:
                Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " = "
                Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, default_code
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Array literals re-emit "[e1, e2, *rest]" with splat elements re-prefixed with "*"
from the "ruby_splat" tag the frontend set on splatted entries.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_list_literal" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let elements be proc hir_get_list_elements from HIR with node
    Let element_count be proc list_length from ListCore with elements

    Let elements_code be ""
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than element_count:
        Let elem_node be proc list_get from ListCore with elements, i
        Let elem_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, elem_node
        If proc meta_flag with elem_node, "ruby_splat" is equal to 1:
            Set elem_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with "*", elem_code
        End If

        If i is greater than 0:
            Set elements_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with elements_code, ", "
        End If
        Set elements_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with elements_code, elem_code
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "[", elements_code
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "]"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Hash literals re-emit "{ k => v, ... }". A symbol key emits the "name: value"
shorthand (recovered from the key's "ruby_symbol" tag and its name), and any
other key emits the explicit "key => value" rocket form.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_map_literal" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let entries be proc hir_get_map_entries from HIR with node
    Let entry_count be proc list_length from ListCore with entries

    Let entries_code be ""
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than entry_count:
        Let entry be proc list_get from ListCore with entries, i
        Let key_node be proc hir_get_map_entry_key from HIR with entry
        Let value_node be proc hir_get_map_entry_value from HIR with entry
        Let value_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, value_node

        If i is greater than 0:
            Set entries_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with entries_code, ", "
        End If

        Let key_kind be proc hir_node_type from HIR with key_node
        Let is_symbol_key be 0
        If key_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_STRING_LITERAL:
            If proc meta_flag with key_node, "ruby_symbol" is equal to 1:
                Set is_symbol_key to 1
            End If
        End If

        If is_symbol_key is equal to 1:
            Let sym_name be proc hir_get_string_literal_value from HIR with key_node
            Set entries_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with entries_code, sym_name
            Set entries_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with entries_code, ": "
            Set entries_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with entries_code, value_code
        Otherwise:
            Let key_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, key_node
            Set entries_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with entries_code, key_code
            Set entries_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with entries_code, " => "
            Set entries_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with entries_code, value_code
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "{ ", entries_code
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " }"
    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Statement Generation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Dispatch table for statement-kind to a specialised emitter. The class node serves
both Ruby classes and modules (distinguished by the "ruby_kind" tag). The fallback
treats the node as an expression statement, prepending indent and appending
newline, since any non-statement HIR node reachable here is a side-effecting
expression at statement position, which Ruby tolerates directly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_statement" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, stmt_node as Integer returns String:
    Let node_type be proc hir_node_type from HIR with stmt_node

    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_BLOCK:
        Return proc generate_block with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    End If
    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_CLASS:
        Return proc generate_class with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    End If
    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_FUNCTION:
        Return proc generate_method with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    End If
    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_IF:
        Return proc generate_if_statement with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    End If
    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_WHILE:
        Return proc generate_while_statement with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    End If
    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_FOR_IN:
        Return proc generate_for_in_statement with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    End If
    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_TRY:
        Return proc generate_try_statement with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    End If
    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_RETURN:
        Return proc generate_return_statement with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    End If
    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_BREAK:
        Return proc generate_break_statement with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    End If
    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_CONTINUE:
        Return proc generate_continue_statement with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    End If
    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_YIELD:
        Return proc generate_yield_statement with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    End If
    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_EXPR_STMT:
        Let inner be proc hir_get_expression_statement_expr from HIR with stmt_node
        Let expr_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, inner
        Let indent_es be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
        Let line_es be proc string_concat from StringUtils with indent_es, expr_code
        Set line_es to proc string_concat from StringUtils with line_es, "\n"
        Return line_es
    End If

    Note: Bare expression at statement position.
    Let expr_code2 be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    Let indent2 be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Let result2 be proc string_concat from StringUtils with indent2, expr_code2
    Set result2 to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result2, "\n"
    Return result2
End Process

@Reasoning:
A HIR block emits its statements in order with no separator; each generated
statement already carries its own indentation and trailing newline. Blocks that
carry the "ruby_multiple_assign" tag collapse back into a single comma-form
"a, b = x, y" line; case-chain blocks ("ruby_case") and begin-else blocks pass
through as ordinary statement sequences since their structure is encoded in the
nested if/try nodes.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_block" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    If proc meta_flag with node, "ruby_multiple_assign" is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_multiple_assign with ctx_ptr, node
    End If

    Let statements be proc hir_get_block_statements from HIR with node
    Let stmt_count be 0
    If statements is not equal to 0:
        Set stmt_count to proc list_length from ListCore with statements
    End If

    Let result be ""
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than stmt_count:
        Let stmt_node be proc list_get from ListCore with statements, i
        Let stmt_code be proc generate_statement with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, stmt_code
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
A multiple-assignment block re-collapses its per-target assignment statements into
Ruby's "a, b = x, y" comma form: the left side joins each assignment's lhs and the
right side joins each rhs, both with ", ". This restores the source's parallel
assignment from the structurally-expanded HIR.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_multiple_assign" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let statements be proc hir_get_block_statements from HIR with node
    Let stmt_count be 0
    If statements is not equal to 0:
        Set stmt_count to proc list_length from ListCore with statements
    End If

    Let lhs_code be ""
    Let rhs_code be ""

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than stmt_count:
        Let stmt be proc list_get from ListCore with statements, i
        Let assign_expr be proc hir_get_expression_statement_expr from HIR with stmt
        Let lhs_node be proc hir_get_assign_lhs from HIR with assign_expr
        Let rhs_node be proc hir_get_assign_rhs from HIR with assign_expr

        Let one_lhs be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, lhs_node
        If proc meta_flag with lhs_node, "ruby_splat" is equal to 1:
            Set one_lhs to proc string_concat from StringUtils with "*", one_lhs
        End If
        Let one_rhs be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, rhs_node

        If i is greater than 0:
            Set lhs_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with lhs_code, ", "
            Set rhs_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with rhs_code, ", "
        End If
        Set lhs_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with lhs_code, one_lhs
        Set rhs_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with rhs_code, one_rhs
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Let indent_s be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with indent_s, lhs_code
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " = "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, rhs_code
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\n"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
A HIR class emits Ruby "class Name [< Super] ... end", or "module Name ... end"
when tagged "ruby_kind"="module". The members (methods and other body statements)
are emitted indented; the superclass, when present, is generated as an expression
for the "< Super" clause. The singleton "class << self" form is re-emitted from
its tag.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_class" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let class_name be proc hir_get_class_name from HIR with node

    Let keyword be "class"
    If proc meta_is with node, "ruby_kind", "module" is equal to 1:
        Set keyword to "module"
    End If

    Let result be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr

    If proc meta_flag with node, "ruby_singleton_class" is equal to 1:
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "class << "
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, class_name
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\n"
    Otherwise:
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, keyword
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " "
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, class_name

        Let base be proc hir_get_base_class from HIR with node
        If base is not equal to 0:
            Let base_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, base
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " < "
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, base_code
        End If
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\n"
    End If

    proc indent with ctx_ptr
    Let members be proc hir_get_class_members from HIR with node
    Let member_count be 0
    If members is not equal to 0:
        Set member_count to proc list_length from ListCore with members
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than member_count:
        Let member be proc list_get from ListCore with members, i
        Let member_code be proc generate_statement with ctx_ptr, member
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, member_code
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc dedent with ctx_ptr

    Let end_indent be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, end_indent
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "end\n"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
A HIR function emits Ruby "def name(params) body end". A singleton method (tagged
"ruby_singleton_method") prefixes "self." onto the name to re-emit the
"def self.name" form. Parameters are joined with their Ruby spellings and the body
is generated indented. Ruby's implicit return means the final return (tagged
"ruby_implicit_return") emits its bare value.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_method" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let func_name be proc hir_get_function_name from HIR with node
    Let params_code be proc generate_method_params with ctx_ptr, node
    Let body_node be proc hir_get_function_body from HIR with node

    Let result be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "def "
    If proc meta_flag with node, "ruby_singleton_method" is equal to 1:
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "self."
    End If
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, func_name
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with params_code, "" is equal to 0:
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "("
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, params_code
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ")"
    End If
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\n"

    proc indent with ctx_ptr
    Let body_code be proc generate_statement with ctx_ptr, body_node
    proc dedent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, body_code

    Let end_indent be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, end_indent
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "end\n"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Method parameters reuse the parameter machinery: read the function's parameter
list and join each parameter's Ruby spelling with ", ".
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_method_params" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let params be proc hir_get_parameters from HIR with node
    Let param_list be proc hir_get_parameter_list from HIR with params
    Let param_count be 0
    If param_list is not equal to 0:
        Set param_count to proc list_length from ListCore with param_list
    End If

    Let result be ""
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than param_count:
        Let param_node be proc list_get from ListCore with param_list, i
        Let param_code be proc generate_parameter with ctx_ptr, param_node
        If i is greater than 0:
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ", "
        End If
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, param_code
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby if/unless re-emits "if COND ... [elsif/else] ... end" (or "unless" with the
condition's negation undone when the "ruby_unless" tag is set). The else branch may
be a nested HIR if (an elsif, tagged "ruby_elsif", emitted as "elsif COND") or a
plain block (the final else). Building the chain inline keeps the elsif structure.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_if_statement" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let condition_node be proc hir_get_if_condition from HIR with node
    Let then_node be proc hir_get_if_then from HIR with node
    Let else_node be proc hir_get_if_else from HIR with node

    Let is_unless be proc meta_flag with node, "ruby_unless"

    Let cond_code be ""
    If is_unless is equal to 1:
        Note: condition was negated by the frontend; recover the original operand.
        Let inner_operand be proc hir_get_unary_operand from HIR with condition_node
        Set cond_code to proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, inner_operand
    Otherwise:
        Set cond_code to proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, condition_node
    End If

    Let keyword be "if "
    If is_unless is equal to 1:
        Set keyword to "unless "
    End If

    Let result be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, keyword
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, cond_code
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\n"

    proc indent with ctx_ptr
    Let then_code be proc generate_statement with ctx_ptr, then_node
    proc dedent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, then_code

    If else_node is not equal to 0:
        Let tail_code be proc generate_if_tail with ctx_ptr, else_node
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, tail_code
    End If

    Let end_indent be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, end_indent
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "end\n"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
The if-tail emits "elsif COND ... [tail]" for a nested HIR if tagged "ruby_elsif"
(recursing for chained elsifs and a final else), or "else ... " for a plain block.
This reconstructs Ruby's elsif/else chain without the trailing "end" (the outer if
emits the single closing "end").
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_if_tail" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, else_node as Integer returns String:
    Let node_type be proc hir_node_type from HIR with else_node

    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_IF:
        If proc meta_flag with else_node, "ruby_elsif" is equal to 1:
            Let condition_node be proc hir_get_if_condition from HIR with else_node
            Let then_node be proc hir_get_if_then from HIR with else_node
            Let inner_else be proc hir_get_if_else from HIR with else_node

            Let cond_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, condition_node

            Let result be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "elsif "
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, cond_code
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\n"

            proc indent with ctx_ptr
            Let then_code be proc generate_statement with ctx_ptr, then_node
            proc dedent with ctx_ptr
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, then_code

            If inner_else is not equal to 0:
                Let next_code be proc generate_if_tail with ctx_ptr, inner_else
                Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, next_code
            End If
            Return result
        End If
    End If

    Note: Plain else block.
    Let else_indent be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Let result2 be proc string_concat from StringUtils with else_indent, "else\n"

    proc indent with ctx_ptr
    Let else_code be proc generate_statement with ctx_ptr, else_node
    proc dedent with ctx_ptr
    Set result2 to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result2, else_code
    Return result2
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby while/until re-emits "while COND ... end" or "until COND ... end". The until
form recovers its original condition by unwrapping the frontend's logical-not
negation, preserving the source boolean expression.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_while_statement" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let condition_node be proc hir_get_while_condition from HIR with node
    Let body_node be proc hir_get_while_body from HIR with node

    Let is_until be proc meta_flag with node, "ruby_until"

    Let cond_code be ""
    Let keyword be "while "
    If is_until is equal to 1:
        Set keyword to "until "
        Let inner_operand be proc hir_get_unary_operand from HIR with condition_node
        Set cond_code to proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, inner_operand
    Otherwise:
        Set cond_code to proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, condition_node
    End If

    Let result be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, keyword
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, cond_code
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\n"

    proc indent with ctx_ptr
    Let body_code be proc generate_statement with ctx_ptr, body_node
    proc dedent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, body_code

    Let end_indent be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, end_indent
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "end\n"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby's for-in re-emits "for var in iterable ... end" from the HIR for-in node's
variable name, iterable expression and body block.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_for_in_statement" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let var_name be proc hir_get_for_in_variable from HIR with node
    Let iterable_node be proc hir_get_for_in_iterable from HIR with node
    Let body_node be proc hir_get_for_in_body from HIR with node

    Let iterable_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, iterable_node

    Let result be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "for "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, var_name
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " in "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, iterable_code
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\n"

    proc indent with ctx_ptr
    Let body_code be proc generate_statement with ctx_ptr, body_node
    proc dedent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, body_code

    Let end_indent be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, end_indent
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "end\n"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
A HIR try re-emits Ruby's "begin ... rescue ... [else] [ensure] end". The try body,
each catch clause (as a "rescue [Types] [=> var]" block), the optional begin-else
body (recovered from "ruby_begin_else_body" metadata) and the finally block (as
"ensure") are emitted in Ruby's canonical clause order.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_try_statement" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let result be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "begin\n"

    Let try_block be proc hir_get_try_block from HIR with node
    proc indent with ctx_ptr
    Let try_code be proc generate_statement with ctx_ptr, try_block
    proc dedent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, try_code

    Let catches be proc hir_get_catch_clauses from HIR with node
    Let catch_count be 0
    If catches is not equal to 0:
        Set catch_count to proc list_length from ListCore with catches
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than catch_count:
        Let catch_clause be proc list_get from ListCore with catches, i
        Let catch_code be proc generate_rescue_clause with ctx_ptr, catch_clause
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, catch_code
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Let else_body be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with node, "ruby_begin_else_body"
    If else_body is not equal to 0:
        Let else_indent be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, else_indent
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "else\n"
        proc indent with ctx_ptr
        Let else_code be proc generate_statement with ctx_ptr, else_body
        proc dedent with ctx_ptr
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, else_code
    End If

    Let finally_block be proc hir_get_finally_block from HIR with node
    If finally_block is not equal to 0:
        Let ensure_indent be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ensure_indent
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "ensure\n"
        proc indent with ctx_ptr
        Let ensure_code be proc generate_statement with ctx_ptr, finally_block
        proc dedent with ctx_ptr
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ensure_code
    End If

    Let end_indent be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, end_indent
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "end\n"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
A HIR catch re-emits a Ruby "rescue [TypeList] [=> var]" clause: the catch type
plus any extra rescue types (recovered from "ruby_rescue_extra_types" metadata)
form the comma-separated type list, the catch variable becomes the "=> var"
binding, and the catch body is emitted indented.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_rescue_clause" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, clause as Integer returns String:
    Let result be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "rescue"

    Let type_name be proc hir_get_catch_type from HIR with clause
    If type_name is not equal to 0:
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " "
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, type_name

        Let extra be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with clause, "ruby_rescue_extra_types"
        If extra is not equal to 0:
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ", "
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, extra
        End If
    End If

    Let var_name be proc hir_get_catch_variable from HIR with clause
    If var_name is not equal to 0:
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " => "
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, var_name
    End If

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\n"

    Let body be proc hir_get_catch_body from HIR with clause
    proc indent with ctx_ptr
    Let body_code be proc generate_statement with ctx_ptr, body
    proc dedent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, body_code
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby's return re-emits "return [value]". An implicit return (tagged
"ruby_implicit_return") emits only its bare value expression as the last line of a
method, matching Ruby's last-expression-is-the-result semantics.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_return_statement" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let value_node be proc hir_get_return_value from HIR with node
    Let indent_s be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr

    If proc meta_flag with node, "ruby_implicit_return" is equal to 1:
        If value_node is equal to 0:
            Return proc string_concat from StringUtils with indent_s, "\n"
        End If
        Let value_code_i be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, value_node
        Let line_i be proc string_concat from StringUtils with indent_s, value_code_i
        Set line_i to proc string_concat from StringUtils with line_i, "\n"
        Return line_i
    End If

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with indent_s, "return"
    If value_node is not equal to 0:
        Let value_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, value_node
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " "
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, value_code
    End If
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\n"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby's break re-emits "break [value]"; a value-carrying break recovers its value
from "ruby_break_value" metadata.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_break_statement" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let result be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "break"

    Let value_node be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with node, "ruby_break_value"
    If value_node is not equal to 0:
        Let value_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, value_node
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " "
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, value_code
    End If
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\n"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
A HIR continue tagged "ruby_next" re-emits Ruby's "next [value]". The optional
carried value is recovered from "ruby_next_value" metadata.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_continue_statement" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let result be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "next"

    Let value_node be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with node, "ruby_next_value"
    If value_node is not equal to 0:
        Let value_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, value_node
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " "
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, value_code
    End If
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\n"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
A HIR yield re-emits Ruby's "yield [args]". The yield's value (stored as the
return-value slot by the frontend) is a single expression or, when tagged
"ruby_yield_multi", a list literal whose elements are the comma-separated yield
arguments.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_yield_statement" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let value_node be proc hir_get_return_value from HIR with node
    Let indent_s be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with indent_s, "yield"

    If value_node is not equal to 0:
        If proc meta_flag with node, "ruby_yield_multi" is equal to 1:
            Let elements be proc hir_get_list_elements from HIR with value_node
            Let elem_count be proc list_length from ListCore with elements
            Let args_code be ""
            Let i be 0
            While i is less than elem_count:
                Let elem be proc list_get from ListCore with elements, i
                Let elem_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, elem
                If i is greater than 0:
                    Set args_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with args_code, ", "
                End If
                Set args_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with args_code, elem_code
                Set i to i plus 1
            End While
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " "
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, args_code
        Otherwise:
            Let single_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, value_node
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " "
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, single_code
        End If
    End If

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\n"
    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Top-Level Generation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Iterates the module's declaration list (the top-level statements added by the
frontend's translate_program). Each declaration is generated as a statement so the
result includes any leading keywords and trailing newlines, producing a flat Ruby
script that runs in original declaration order.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_module" takes ctx_ptr as Integer returns String:
    Let ctx as RubyCodeGenContext be ctx_ptr

    Let declarations be proc hir_get_declarations from HIR with ctx.hir_module
    Let decl_count be 0
    If declarations is not equal to 0:
        Set decl_count to proc list_length from ListCore with declarations
    End If

    Let result be ""
    Let decl_index be 0
    While decl_index is less than decl_count:
        Let decl_node be proc list_get from ListCore with declarations, decl_index
        Let decl_code be proc generate_statement with ctx_ptr, decl_node
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, decl_code
        Set decl_index to decl_index plus 1
    End While

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Public entry point used by the translation driver. Wraps the create-context +
generate-module pair so callers do not manage the context lifecycle. The returned
String holds the complete Ruby source.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_ruby_code" takes hir_module as Integer returns String:
    Let ctx be proc create_codegen_context with hir_module
    Let code be proc generate_module with ctx
    Return code
End Process

@Reasoning:
Predicate accessor for the had_error sentinel. Returns the raw integer (0/1)
because Boolean is implemented as Integer in the bootstrap layer.
@End Reasoning
Process called "had_codegen_errors" takes ctx_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ctx as RubyCodeGenContext be ctx_ptr
    Return ctx.had_error
End Process

@Reasoning:
Exposes the accumulated errors list pointer so the driver can iterate diagnostic
messages. The returned list is owned by the context.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_codegen_errors" takes ctx_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ctx as RubyCodeGenContext be ctx_ptr
    Return ctx.errors
End Process
